# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: finite-difference-time-domain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] In many physical problems, such as acoustics, electromagnetics, and fluid dynamics, waves naturally propagate into an infinite or semi-infinite space.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] However, numerical methods like finite difference or finite element methods require a finite, truncated grid to remain computationally feasible.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] Without an effective absorbing boundary condition, waves reaching the artificial boundary of the simulation would reflect back into the interior, causing non-physical interference and spurious echoes that contaminate the results.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] A perfect absorbing boundary condition would be nonlocal, meaning that the behavior at one point on the boundary depends on the history of the wave field at all other points on the boundary.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] While mathematically exact, these non-local conditions are often too computationally expensive for large-scale simulations.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] Consequently, most practical absorbing boundary conditions utilize local approximations based on the differential properties of the wave field.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] Beyond purely mathematical boundary operators, many implementations utilize material absorbers such as the perfectly matched layer, which simulate an artificial physical region where waves are gradually attenuated through absorptive properties before they reach the simulation's edge.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] Early absorbing boundary conditions, adopted until the 1970s, were based on the application of Sommerfeld radiation condition; these are denoted as the zeroth-order boundary conditions.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] From the late 1970s to the mid-1980s, low-order absorbing boundary conditions, such as Bayliss–Turkel and Engquist–Majda absorbing boundary conditions were introduced.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/absorbing-boundary-condition] The 1990s saw the introduction of perfectly matched layers, as well as higher-order local boundary conditions.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] In mathematics, the **convergence condition by Courant–Friedrichs–Lewy** (CFL) is a necessary condition for convergence while solving certain partial differential equations (usually hyperbolic PDEs) numerically.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] It arises in the numerical analysis of explicit time integration schemes, when these are used for the numerical solution.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] As a consequence, the time step must be less than a certain upper bound, given a fixed spatial increment, in many explicit time-marching computer simulations; otherwise, the simulation produces incorrect or unstable results.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The condition is named after Richard Courant, Kurt Friedrichs, and Hans Lewy who described it in their 1928 paper.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The principle behind the condition is that, for example, if a wave is moving across a discrete spatial grid and we want to compute its amplitude at discrete time steps of equal duration, then this duration must be less than the time for the wave to travel to adjacent grid points.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] As a corollary, when the grid point separation is reduced, the upper limit for the time step also decreases.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The spatial coordinates and the time are discrete-valued independent variables, which are placed at regular distances called the *interval length* and the *time step*, respectively.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] Using these names, the CFL condition relates the length of the time step to a function of the interval lengths of each spatial coordinate and of the maximum speed that information can travel in the physical space.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] Operatively, the CFL condition is commonly prescribed for those terms of the finite-difference approximation of general partial differential equations that model the advection phenomenon.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The value of $C_{\max }$ changes with the method used to solve the discretised equation, especially depending on whether the method is explicit or implicit.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] If an explicit (time-marching) solver is used then typically $C_{\max }=1$ .
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] Implicit (matrix) solvers are usually less sensitive to numerical instability and so larger values of $C_{\max }$ may be tolerated.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] with the obvious meanings of the symbols involved.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The interval length is not required to be the same for each spatial variable $\Delta x_{i},i=1,\ldots ,n$ .
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] This "degree of freedom" can be used to somewhat optimize the value of the time step for a particular problem, by varying the values of the different interval to keep it not too small.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] where ${\bf {w}}\in \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ is a vector of arbitrary dimension N and ${\bf {\underline {A}}}\in \mathbb {R} ^{N}\times \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ is accordingly a matrix of order N .
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] where $|\lambda |_{\max }$ is the magnitude of the largest eigenvalue of the matrix ${\bf {\underline {A}}}$ .
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The extension to multiple dimensions follows the logic described above.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Finite difference schemes for time-dependent partial differential equations (PDEs) have been employed for many years in computational fluid dynamics problems, including the idea of using centered finite difference operators on staggered grids in space and time to achieve second-order accuracy.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The novelty of Yee's FDTD scheme, presented in his seminal 1966 paper, was to apply centered finite difference operators on staggered grids in space and time for each electric and magnetic vector field component in Maxwell's curl equations.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The descriptor "Finite-difference time-domain" and its corresponding "FDTD" acronym were originated by Allen Taflove in 1980.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Since about 1990, FDTD techniques have emerged as primary means to computationally model many scientific and engineering problems dealing with electromagnetic wave interactions with material structures.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] In 2006, an estimated 2,000 FDTD-related publications appeared in the science and engineering literature (see Popularity).
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] As of 2013, there are at least 25 commercial/proprietary FDTD software vendors; 13 free-software/open-source-software FDTD projects; and 2 freeware/closed-source FDTD projects, some not for commercial use (see External links).
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] An appreciation of the basis, technical development, and possible future of FDTD numerical techniques for Maxwell's equations can be developed by first considering their history.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The following lists some of the key publications in this area.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] When Maxwell's differential equations are examined, it can be seen that the change in the E-field in time (the time derivative) is dependent on the change in the H-field across space (the curl).
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] This results in the basic FDTD time-stepping relation that, at any point in space, the updated value of the E-field in time is dependent on the stored value of the E-field and the numerical curl of the local distribution of the H-field in space.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The H-field is time-stepped in a similar manner.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] At any point in space, the updated value of the H-field in time is dependent on the stored value of the H-field and the numerical curl of the local distribution of the E-field in space.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Iterating the E-field and H-field updates results in a marching-in-time process wherein sampled-data analogs of the continuous electromagnetic waves under consideration propagate in a numerical grid stored in the computer memory.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] This description holds true for 1-D, 2-D, and 3-D FDTD techniques.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] When multiple dimensions are considered, calculating the numerical curl can become complicated.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Kane Yee's seminal 1966 paper proposed spatially staggering the vector components of the E-field and H-field about rectangular unit cells of a Cartesian computational grid so that each E-field vector component is located midway between a pair of H-field vector components, and conversely.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] This scheme, now known as a **Yee lattice**, has proven to be very robust, and remains at the core of many current FDTD software constructs.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Furthermore, Yee proposed a leapfrog scheme for marching in time wherein the E-field and H-field updates are staggered so that E-field updates are conducted midway during each time-step between successive H-field updates, and conversely.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] On the plus side, this explicit time-stepping scheme avoids the need to solve simultaneous equations, and furthermore yields dissipation-free numerical wave propagation.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] On the minus side, this scheme mandates an upper bound on the time-step to ensure numerical stability.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] As a result, certain classes of simulations can require many thousands of time-steps for completion.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] To implement an FDTD solution of Maxwell's equations, a computational domain must first be established.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The computational domain is simply the physical region over which the simulation will be performed.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The E and H fields are determined at every point in space within that computational domain.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The material of each cell within the computational domain must be specified.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Typically, the material is either free-space (air), metal, or dielectric.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Any material can be used as long as the permeability, permittivity, and conductivity are specified.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The permittivity of dispersive materials in tabular form cannot be directly substituted into the FDTD scheme.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Instead, it can be approximated using multiple Debye, Drude, Lorentz or critical point terms.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] This approximation can be obtained using open fitting programs and does not necessarily have physical meaning.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Once the computational domain and the grid materials are established, a source is specified.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The source can be current on a wire, applied electric field or impinging plane wave.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] In the last case FDTD can be used to simulate light scattering from arbitrary shaped objects, planar periodic structures at various incident angles, and photonic band structure of infinite periodic structures.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Since the E and H fields are determined directly, the output of the simulation is usually the E or H field at a point or a series of points within the computational domain.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The simulation evolves the E and H fields forward in time.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Processing may be done on the E and H fields returned by the simulation.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Data processing may also occur while the simulation is ongoing.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] While the FDTD technique computes electromagnetic fields within a compact spatial region, scattered and/or radiated far fields can be obtained via near-to-far-field transformations.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Due to the linearity of the FDTD method, the region of stability of the FDTD method may be determined by Von Neumann stability analysis.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] This method assumes that electric and magnetic fields are proportional to a monochromatic complex exponential.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] After a single time-step, the magnitude amplitude of the stable fields need to remain the same or less.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] This leads to the Courant–Friedrichs–Lewy condition, which describes the relationship of the FDTD parameters to ensure stability.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Every modeling technique has strengths and weaknesses, and the FDTD method is no different.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The most commonly used grid truncation techniques for open-region FDTD modeling problems are the Mur absorbing boundary condition (ABC), the Liao ABC, and various perfectly matched layer (PML) formulations.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The Mur and Liao techniques are simpler than PML.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] However, PML (which is technically an absorbing region rather than a boundary condition *per se*) can provide orders-of-magnitude lower reflections.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Berenger in a seminal 1994 paper in the Journal of Computational Physics.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Since 1994, Berenger's original split-field implementation has been modified and extended to the uniaxial PML (UPML), the convolutional PML (CPML), and the higher-order PML.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The latter two PML formulations have increased ability to absorb evanescent waves, and therefore can in principle be placed closer to a simulated scattering or radiating structure than Berenger's original formulation.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] To reduce undesired numerical reflection from the PML additional back absorbing layers technique can be used.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] The sources of error in FDTD calculations are well understood, and can be bounded to permit accurate models for a very large variety of electromagnetic wave interaction problems.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] FDTD treats impulsive behavior naturally.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Being a time-domain technique, FDTD directly calculates the impulse response of an electromagnetic system.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Therefore, a single FDTD simulation can provide either ultrawideband temporal waveforms or the sinusoidal steady-state response at any frequency within the excitation spectrum.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] FDTD treats nonlinear behavior naturally.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Being a time-domain technique, FDTD directly calculates the nonlinear response of an electromagnetic system.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] This allows natural hybriding of FDTD with sets of auxiliary differential equations that describe nonlinearities from either the classical or semi-classical standpoint.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] One research frontier is the development of hybrid algorithms which join FDTD classical electrodynamics models with phenomena arising from quantum electrodynamics, especially vacuum fluctuations, such as the Casimir effect.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] With FDTD, specifying a new structure to be modeled is reduced to a problem of mesh generation rather than the potentially complex reformulation of an integral equation.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] For example, FDTD requires no calculation of structure-dependent Green functions.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Parallel-processing computer architectures have come to dominate supercomputing.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] FDTD scales with high efficiency on parallel-processing CPU-based computers, and extremely well on recently developed GPU-based accelerator technology.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Computer visualization capabilities are increasing rapidly.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] While this trend positively influences all numerical techniques, it is of particular advantage to FDTD methods, which generate time-marched arrays of field quantities suitable for use in color videos to illustrate the field dynamics.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Anisotropy is treated naturally by the FDTD method.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Yee cells, having components in each Cartesian direction, can be easily configured with anisotropic characteristics.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/finite-difference-time-domain-method] Taflove has argued that these factors combine to suggest that FDTD will remain one of the dominant computational electrodynamics techniques (as well as potentially other multiphysics problems).
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/numerical-dispersion] In computational mathematics, **numerical dispersion** is a difficulty with computer simulations of continua (such as fluids) wherein the simulated medium exhibits a higher dispersivity than the true medium.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/numerical-dispersion] This phenomenon can be particularly egregious when the system should not be dispersive at all, for example a fluid acquiring some spurious dispersion in a numerical model.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/numerical-dispersion] It occurs whenever the dispersion relation for the finite difference approximation is nonlinear.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/numerical-dispersion] For these reasons, it is often seen as a numerical error.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/numerical-dispersion] Numerical dispersion is often identified, linked and compared with numerical diffusion, another artifact of similar origin.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/numerical-dispersion] The amount and character of the difference depends on the system being simulated and the type of discretization that is used.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] A **perfectly matched layer** (**PML**) is an artificial absorbing layer for wave equations, commonly used to truncate computational regions in numerical methods to simulate problems with open boundaries, especially in the FDTD and FE methods.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] Berenger's original formulation is called a **split-field PML**, because it splits the electromagnetic fields into two unphysical fields in the PML region.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] A later formulation that has become more popular because of its simplicity and efficiency is called **uniaxial PML** or **UPML**, in which the PML is described as an artificial anisotropic absorbing material.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] This viewpoint allows PMLs to be derived for inhomogeneous media such as waveguides, as well as for other coordinate systems and wave equations.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] Specifically, for a PML designed to absorb waves propagating in the *x* direction, the following transformation is included in the wave equation.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] where $\omega$ is the angular frequency and $\sigma$ is some function of *x*.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] where we have taken a planewave propagating in the +*x* direction (for $k>0$ ) and applied the transformation (analytic continuation) to complex coordinates: $x\to x+{\frac {i}{\omega }}\int ^{x}\sigma (x')dx'$ , or equivalently $dx\to dx(1+i\sigma /\omega )$ .
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] The same coordinate transformation causes waves to attenuate whenever their *x* dependence is in the form $e^{ikx}$ for some propagation constant *k*: this includes planewaves propagating at some angle with the *x* axis and also transverse modes of a waveguide.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] The above coordinate transformation can be left as-is in the transformed wave equations, or can be combined with the material description (e.g. the permittivity and permeability in Maxwell's equations) to form a UPML description.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] The coefficient σ/ω depends upon frequency—this is so the attenuation rate is proportional to *k*/ω, which is independent of frequency in a homogeneous material (not including material dispersion, e.g. for vacuum) because of the dispersion relation between ω and *k*.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] Perfectly matched layers, in their original form, only attenuate propagating waves; purely evanescent waves (exponentially decaying fields) oscillate in the PML but do not decay more quickly.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] PML is widely used and has become the absorbing boundary technique of choice in much of computational electromagnetism.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] Although it works well in most cases, there are a few important cases in which it breaks down, suffering from unavoidable reflections or even exponential growth.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] One caveat with perfectly matched layers is that they are only reflectionless for the *exact*, continuous wave equation.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] Once the wave equation is discretized for simulation on a computer, some small numerical reflections appear (which vanish with increasing resolution).
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] For this reason, the PML absorption coefficient σ is typically turned on gradually from zero (e.g. quadratically) over a short distance on the scale of the wavelength of the wave.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] In certain materials, there are "backward-wave" solutions in which group and phase velocity are opposite to one another.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] Fortunately, there is a simple solution in a left-handed medium (for which all waves are backwards): merely flip the sign of σ.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] A complication, however, is that physical left-handed materials are dispersive: they are only left-handed within a certain frequency range, and therefore the σ coefficient must be made frequency-dependent.
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] Another important limitation of PML is that it requires that the medium be invariant in the direction orthogonal to the boundary, in order to support the analytic continuation of the solution to complex coordinates (the complex "coordinate stretching").
[src:finite-difference-time-domain/perfectly-matched-layer] As a consequence, the PML approach is no longer valid (no longer reflectionless at infinite resolution) in the case of periodic media (e.g. photonic crystals or phononic crystals) or even simply a waveguide that enters the boundary at an oblique angle.
